2.3.0 Estimating Grade and Sub-Grade

We've used a multi classification model to predict the grade and sub grade process. Unlike for the previous model only different configuration of XGBoost were used. Our tuning process was similar to that used by previous model:

  • Selection of optimal feature transformers (using grid search).
  • Hypertuning for different traget metrics (PR-AUC, logloss and macro F1) score to select the optimal hyperparameters.

See the appendices for more details.

2.3.1 Training and Evaluation

We've selected a configuration tuned for F1 as our "production" model. However, additional configurations were tested. It's worth noting that tuning for PR-AUC achieved comparable performance however the training time increase significantly, the configuration used max_depth = 12, learning_rate while= 0.2 while 7/0.3 and setting gamma to 0.1 (minimum reduction in loss required to make a further partition on a leaf node of the tree) instead of 0.0 was sufficient.

While the performance for A,B,C grades is relatively acceptable (F1 > ~0.8) performance when predicting the lower grades is very poor (especially for grade G which is almost never classified correctly).

As we have learnt when building our default risk model there difference in returns and other features does not vary as much for lower quality grades which might make it hard to distinguish them. Therefore we'll use the same approach and merge E-F-G grades into a single group.

Predicting Sub-grades

We've attempted to build a model which predicts individual sub-grades (e.g. A1, A2 ... G5) in addition to top level grades. An XGBoost multi-classificaiton model was used, however the performance was unsatisfactory. We've included the overal performance summary and feature importances below. However, we decide to not provide an indepth analysis because the model would not be useful for any practical applications (a different approach would probably suit this problem better due to the high number of classes and their ordinal nature)

Conclusion

  • As could have been expected the multi classification model performs significantly worse than a binary classifier.

  • Performance when predicting the lower grades, especially E-F-G is poor. This might indicate that:

    • The algorithm used for setting the grades is not entirely fixed and the provided features can't be consistently. Classes E, F, and G might have features that are not as distinct from each other as those separating A, B, and C. This overlap can confuse the model, especially if the ordinal relationship leads to gradual changes in feature values across classes.
    • The features used might not effectively capture the variance within E, F, G, or the ordinal relationship between classes. Features that are good at differentiating A, B, C might not scale well into distinguishing E, F, G.

  • The model complexity might not be sufficient to capture the nuances that would differentiate between E, F, and G. This could be due to too few trees, shallow trees, or not enough iterations. e.g.: If XGBoost is tuned with a low depth parameter, it might capture the broad differences between A, B, C well but fail to model the subtleties needed for E, F, G. However we have trained a configuration with a more complex model and the performance was not signficantly different. This might allow use to reject this hypothesis but additional testing and analysis might be necessary.
